After these events, the ''Nihon Shoki'' narrative continues that Sujin's aunt {{Nihongo|{{ill|Princess Yamato Totohi Momoso|lt=Yamatototohimomoso-hime|en}}|倭迹迹日百襲媛命}}, the daughter of the seventh emperor {{ill|Emperor Kōrei|Kōrei|en}}, acted as a {{ill|Miko|shrine maiden|en}}, and was possessed by a god who identified himself as {{ill|Ōmononushi|en}},<ref name="aston150–164" /><ref name=":3">{{Cite journal |last=Ellwood |first=Robert S. |date=1990 |title=The Sujin Religious Revolution |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/30234018 |journal=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies |volume=17 |issue=2/3 |pages=199–217 |issn=0304-1042}}</ref> possibly the same entity as Yamato Okunitama. {{ill|Ichishi no Nagaochi|ja|市磯長尾市|en:draft|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Ichishi no Nagaochi}} would conduct the rites pertaining to Okunitama, replacing the emaciated {{Ill|Nunaki-iri-hime|ja|渟名城入姫命|en:draft|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Nunaki-iri-hime}}.<ref name=":3" /> {{ill|Ichishi no Nagaochi|ja|市磯長尾市|en:draft|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Ichishi no Nagaochi}} would be the ancestor of the {{ill|Yamato no Kuni no Miyatsuko|Yamato clan|en}}.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Page:Nihongi by Aston.djvu/208 - Wikisource, the free online library |url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Page:Nihongi_by_Aston.djvu/208 |access-date=2023-10-24 |website=en.wikisource.org |language=en}}</ref> This replacement is taken as a shift towards a more patriarchal religion.<ref name=":3" />

