{{Ill|Nunaki-iri-hime|ja|渟名城入姫命|draft}} (渟名城入姫命) was a {{ill|Japanese|en}} {{ill|Princess|en}}.<ref name="aston150–164">{{cite book |author=Aston, William George. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_oEfAAAAYAAJ |title=Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697, Volume 2 |date=1896 |publisher=The Japan Society London |isbn=9780524053478 |pages=150–164 |author-link=William George Aston}}</ref>
{{ill|ja:渟名城入姫命|en}}

== Overview ==
The events of her life are primarily characterized in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|NIhon Shoki|en}}.<ref name=":5">{{cite wikisource|year=1896|plaintitle=Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697|wslink=Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697|wspages=151-154|chapter=Book I|publisher=Kegan Paul, Trench, Trübner & Co.|author-first=William George|author-last=Aston|draft}}</ref> Similar events also covered by the ''{{ill|Kogo Shūi|en}}''.<ref name=":6">{{cite book |title=Kogoshūi: Gleanings from Ancient Stories. Translated with an introduction and notes |date=1925 |publisher=Meiji Japan Society |pages=29–30 |translator1-last=Katō |translator1-first=Genchi |translator2-last=Hoshino |translator2-first=Hikoshirō}}</ref>

The narrative relates that pestilence struck during the 5th year of Sujin's rule, and ultimately killed half of the Japanese population. Peasants abandoned their fields in the following year, and rebellion became rampant after eventual events Sujin placed his daughter {{Nihongo|{{Ill|Toyosukiiri-hime|ja|豊鍬入姫命|draft}}|豊鍬入姫命{{ill|ja:豊鍬入姫命|en}}}} in charge of the new shrine, where she would become the first {{ill|Saiō|lt=Ise Saiō|en}}, .<ref name="aston150–164" />.<ref name="aston150–164" />{{efn|During the reign of Sujin's successor {{ill|Emperor Suinin|Suinin|en}}, custody of the sacred treasures were transferred from Toyosukiirihime to Suinin's daughter {{ill|Yamatohime-no-mikoto|lt=Yamatohime|en}}, who took them first to "Sasahata in Uda" to the east of Miwa. Heading north to {{ill|Ōmi Province|en}}, she then traveled eastwards to {{ill|Mino Province|Mino|en}}, then south to {{ill|Ise Province|Ise|en}}, where she received a revelation from Amaterasu:

{{quotation|Now Ama-terasu no Oho-kami instructed Yamato-hime no Mikoto, saying:—"The province of Ise, of the divine wind, is the land whither repair the waves from the eternal world, the successive waves. It is a secluded and pleasant land. In this land I wish to dwell." In compliance, therefore, with the instruction of the Great Goddess, a shrine was erected to her in the province of Ise. Accordingly an {{ill|Saikū|lt=Abstinence Palace|en}} was built at Kaha-kami in Isuzu. This was called the palace of Iso. It was there that Ama-terasu no Oho-kami first descended from Heaven.<ref>{{cite wikisource |author-first= William George |author-last= Aston |chapter= Book I |wslink= Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697 |plaintitle= Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697 |year= 1896 |publisher= Kegan Paul, Trench, Trübner & Co.|wspages=176}}</ref>}}

