This account serves as the origin myth of the {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|Grand Shrine of Ise|en}}, Amaterasu's chief place of worship.}} <ref>https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=8608</ref>.<ref name="Kegan Paul, Trench, Trübner & Co.. [[Wikisource]]-1896" /><ref name="Meiji Japan Society-1925" /> Meanwhile, {{ill|Yamato Okunitama|en}} was entrusted to another daughter named {{Ill|Nunaki-iri-hime|ja|渟名城入姫命|en:draft|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Nunaki-iri-hime}}, but shortly afterwards, her health began to fail. It is recorded that she became [[emaciated|emaciated]] and lost all of her [[hair|hair]], which rendered her unable to perform her duties.<ref name="aston150–164" /> These efforts still did not alleviate the ongoing plague, so Sujin decreed that a {{ill|divination|en}} be performed sometime during the 7th year of his reign, that would involve him making a trip to the plain of Kami-asaji, and invoking the {{Ill|Yaoyorozu no Kami|lt=eighty myriad deities|simple|Yaoyorozu no Kami}}.<ref name="aston150–164" /> This mode of worship is seen as being potentially linked to a social order of greater complexity, and the organization of the deities of the many clans across the region.<ref>{{Citation |title=Contents |date=2017-12-31 |url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/9780824862848-001 |work=Himiko and Japan's Elusive Chiefdom of Yamatai |pages=189-191 |access-date=2023-10-24 |publisher=University of Hawaii Press |isbn=978-0-8248-6284-8}}</ref>

After these events, Sujin's aunt {{Nihongo|{{ill|Princess Yamato Totohi Momoso|lt=Yamatototohimomoso-hime|en}}|倭迹迹日百襲媛命}}, the daughter of the seventh emperor {{ill|Emperor Kōrei|Kōrei|en}}, acted as a {{ill|Miko|shrine maiden|en}}, and was possessed by a god who identified himself as {{ill|Ōmononushi|en}},<ref name="aston150–164" /><ref name="Ellwood-1990">{{Cite journal |last=Ellwood |first=Robert S. |date=1990 |title=The Sujin Religious Revolution |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/30234018 |journal=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies |volume=17 |issue=2/3 |pages=199–217 |issn=0304-1042}}</ref> possibly the same entity as Yamato Okunitama. {{ill|Ichishi no Nagaochi|ja|市磯長尾市|en:draft|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Ichishi no Nagaochi}} would conduct the rites pertaining to Okunitama, replacing the emaciated {{Ill|Nunaki-iri-hime|ja|渟名城入姫命|en:draft|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Nunaki-iri-hime}}.<ref name="Ellwood-1990" /> {{ill|Ichishi no Nagaochi|ja|市磯長尾市|en:draft|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Ichishi no Nagaochi}} would be the ancestor of the {{ill|Yamato no Kuni no Miyatsuko|Yamato clan|en}}.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Page:Nihongi by Aston.djvu/208 - Wikisource, the free online library |url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Page:Nihongi_by_Aston.djvu/208 |access-date=2023-10-24 |website=en.wikisource.org |language=en}}</ref> This replacement is taken as a shift towards a more patriarchal religion.<ref name="Ellwood-1990" />

