After these events, Sujin's aunt {{Nihongo|{{ill|Princess Yamato Totohi Momoso|lt=Yamatototohimomoso-hime|en|12=draft}}|倭迹迹日百襲媛命}}, the daughter of the seventh emperor {{ill|Emperor Kōrei|Kōrei|en|12=draft}}, acted as a {{ill|Miko|shrine maiden|en|12=draft}}, and was possessed by a god who identified himself as {{ill|Ōmononushi|en}},<ref name="aston150–164" /><ref name="Ellwood-1990">{{Cite journal|last=Ellwood |first=Robert S. |date=1990 |title=The Sujin Religious Revolution |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/30234018 |journal=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies |volume=17 |issue=2/3 |pages=199–217 |issn=0304-1042|12=draft}}</ref> possibly the same entity as Yamato Okunitama. {{ill|Ichishi no Nagaochi|ja|市磯長尾市|en:draft|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Ichishi no Nagaochi|8=fr|12=draft}} would conduct the rites pertaining to Okunitama, replacing the emaciated {{Interlanguage link|12=draft|Nunaki-iri-hime|ja|渟名城入姫命|en:draft|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Nunaki-iri-hime|8=fr}}.<ref name="Ellwood-1990" /> {{ill|Ichishi no Nagaochi|ja|市磯長尾市|en:draft|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Ichishi no Nagaochi|8=fr|12=draft}} would be the ancestor of the {{ill|Yamato no Kuni no Miyatsuko|Yamato clan|en|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Page:Nihongi by Aston.djvu/208 - Wikisource, the free online library |url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Page:Nihongi_by_Aston.djvu/208 |access-date=2023-10-24 |website=en.wikisource.org |language=en}}</ref> This replacement is taken as a shift towards a more patriarchal religion.<ref name="Ellwood-1990" />

